{{nihongo foot|'''''Famicom Wars'''''|ファミコンウォーズ|Famikon Wōzu|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a [[Wargame (video games)|wargame]] developed by [[Nintendo]] and [[Intelligent Systems]] and published by Nintendo for the [[Family Computer]]. It was released on August 12, 1988,  in Japan.<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=7844|title=ファミコンウォーズ [ファミコン] / ファミ通.com|website=www.famitsu.com|access-date=2018-07-26}}</ref> It was later re-released on [[Virtual Console]]. It is the first game in the ''[[Wars (series)|Wars]]'' series.

==Gameplay==
[[File:Super Famicom Wars - Title Screen.PNG|thumb|left|Title screen of ''Super Famicom Wars'']]

Players take control of one of two warring [[nation]]s, Red Star and Blue Moon, as they seek to establish turn-based dominance over each other. After selecting which stage to start the game and setting which, if either, player will be controlled by a person, the Red Star army is given the first turn. The objective in each stage is to either capture the enemy's headquarters or destroy all remaining enemy units in one turn. During each turn, the player is given a certain amount of funds which can be used to build units in factories, seaports, and airports under their command; additional funds are earned by conquering cities near their headquarters. Each unit has their own speciality and unique abilities, with ten land units (including two foot soldier units), four air units, and two sea units. Some units have heavier firepower than others, while others provide support to allies. Only foot soldier units are capable of conquering cities, which can then be used to repair or refuel damaged units. There are 15 maps available at the start of the game, with two secret ending maps dependent on which nation the player fights for when playing against the computer.

==Development==
Development of ''Famicom Wars'' began as [[Intelligent Systems]] changed its direction from creating hardware to developing [[simulation game]]s.<ref>[http://fire-emblem.com/shadowdragon/interview/interview1.html Iwata Asks - Fire Emblem: Shadow Dragon<!-- Bot generated title -->] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20101104062134/http://fire-emblem.com/shadowdragon/interview/interview1.html |date=November 4, 2010}}</ref>

==Reception and legacy==
On release, ''[[Famitsu|Famicom Tsūshin]]'' (now ''Famitsu'') scored the Famicom version of the game a 33 out of 40.<ref>30 Point Plus: ファミコンウォーズ. Weekly Famicom Tsūshin. No.257. Pg.40. 12–19 November 1993.</ref><ref name=":0" /> The 1989 "All Soft Catalog" issue of ''Famicom Tsūshin'' included ''Famicom Wars'' in its list of the [[List of video games considered the best|best games of all time]], giving it the [[Strategy video game|Best Simulation]] and Best Commercial [[List of Game of the Year awards|awards]].<ref name="Famitsu1989">{{cite book |chapter='83〜'89 ベストヒットゲーム大賞 |trans-chapter='83〜'89 Best Hit Game Awards |title=ファミコン通信 〜 '89全ソフトカタログ |trans-title=Famicom Tsūshin: '89 All Software Catalog |series=[[Famicom Tsūshin]] |date=15 September 1989 |page=138 |chapter-url=https://cdn-ak.f.st-hatena.com/images/fotolife/M/MULTi88/20200420/20200420025318.jpg}}</ref>

The original ''Famicom Wars'' was followed by a series of sequels which were released only in Japan as well, which includes ''[[Game Boy Wars]]'' in [[1990 in video gaming|1990]] and ''[[Super Famicom Wars]]'' in [[1998 in video gaming|1998]], both which were developed by [[Intelligent Systems]] and [[Nintendo]], as opposed to a sub-series of sequels to the original ''Game Boy Wars'', which were developed and published by [[Hudson Soft]]. The series eventually made its international debut with ''[[Advance Wars]]'', released for the [[Game Boy Advance]] in [[2001 in video gaming|2001]]. The maps from both ''Famicom Wars'' and ''[[Super Famicom Wars]]'' were later included in ''[[Advance Wars]]'' and its sequels.<ref>[http://www.1up.com/games/nintendods/advance-wars-dor/ Accessed 2007-11-25] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629042319/http://www.1up.com/games/nintendods/advance-wars-dor/ |date=2011-06-29}}</ref>

A group of six soldiers from the game appears in the Wii game ''[[Captain Rainbow]]''. The soldiers aspire to win the [[volleyball]] gold medal.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://gonintendo.com/wp-content/uploads/11665_cr1_122_374lo.jpg |title=Archived copy |access-date=2008-08-06 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111020011940/http://gonintendo.com/wp-content/uploads/11665_cr1_122_374lo.jpg |archive-date=2011-10-20}}</ref>

