''Super Famicom Wars'' is an enhanced remake of ''Famicom Wars'' developed by [[Intelligent Systems]] and released for the [[Super Famicom]] on May 1, 1998, exclusively via the [[Nintendo Power (cartridge)|Nintendo Power]] service in commemoration of the tenth anniversary of the original Family Computer version.<ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=7843|title=スーパーファミコンウォーズ [スーパーファミコン] / ファミ通.com|website=www.famitsu.com|access-date=2018-08-20|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180821011837/https://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?a=page_h_title&title_id=7843|archive-date=2018-08-21|url-status=live}}</ref>

Improvements over the original ''Famicom Wars'' include the inclusion of 8 new types of units in addition to the 16 original units, a faster decision-making process for the CPU, the introduction of Reconnaissance Mode (also known as "Fog of War" mode in later localizations, in which enemy units are invisible during the player's turn when they're not in proximity to the player's units) and the maximum amount of deployed units being increased from 48 to 60 units.<ref name="SFC Wars homepage">{{cite web|url=https://www.nintendo.co.jp/n02/shvc/bfwj/index.html|title=スーパーファミコンウォーズ|language=Japanese}}</ref> In addition to the original campaign between the Red Star and Blue Moon armies, there's a new campaign also consisting of 17 maps involving two new factions, Green Earth and Yellow Comet. In addition there is a 4-players mode consisting of 10 maps involving all four factions. This brings the total count of maps to 44. The player can also assign one of seven generals to each army, which mainly affects what kind of strategies the CPU will employ, although some of the generals do provide passive benefits even when assigned to a player-controlled faction.

The game was digitally released on Nintendo's Japanese [[Virtual Console]] for [[Wii]],<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.engadget.com/2010/02/16/japanese-nintendo-downloads-super-famicom-wars-diner-dash/|title=Japanese Nintendo downloads: Super Famicom Wars, Diner Dash|work=Engadget|access-date=2018-08-20|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180820234859/https://www.engadget.com/2010/02/16/japanese-nintendo-downloads-super-famicom-wars-diner-dash/|archive-date=2018-08-20|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Wii U]],<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Bivens |first1=Danny |title=Japan eShop Round-Up (10/02/2013) |work=Nintendo World Report |date=2013-10-03 |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/feature/35559/japan-eshop-round-up-10022013 |access-date=2018-09-02 |df=mdy-all}}</ref> and [[3DS]] platforms.<ref>{{Cite web |last1=Bivens |first1=Danny |title=Super Famicom Wars, Live A Live and More Hit 3DS eShop in Japan - News |work=Nintendo World Report |date=2016-11-28 |url=http://www.nintendoworldreport.com/news/43724/super-famicom-wars-live-a-live-and-more-hit-3ds-eshop-in-japan |access-date=2018-09-02 |df=mdy-all}}</ref>

An English-language [[Fan translation of video games|fan translation]] was released in 2018.<ref name=":2">{{Cite news|url=http://www.siliconera.com/2018/01/02/fan-translation-makes-super-famicom-wars-playable-english/|title=Fan Translation Makes Super Famicom Wars Playable In English - Siliconera|date=2018-01-02|work=Siliconera|access-date=2018-08-21|language=en-US|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180107203733/http://www.siliconera.com/2018/01/02/fan-translation-makes-super-famicom-wars-playable-english/|archive-date=2018-01-07|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name="NintendoLife">{{Cite news|url=http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2017/12/super_famicom_wars_and_princess_minerva_translated_to_english|title='Super Famicom Wars' And 'Princess Minerva' Translated to English|date=2017-12-26|work=Nintendo Life|access-date=2018-08-20|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180130101800/http://www.nintendolife.com/news/2017/12/super_famicom_wars_and_princess_minerva_translated_to_english|archive-date=2018-01-30|url-status=live}}</ref>

